Part I - (Dataset Exploration Title)¶

by (Adekemi Kadri)¶

Introduction¶

Prosper Marketplace, Inc. is a peer-to-peer lending company based in San Francisco, California. This data set includes 113,937 loans, each with 81 variables such as loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many more.

Univariate Visualisation¶

Questions for the data visualisation¶

  1. How long do borrowers have to pay their loan back?
  2. What is the occupation and monthly income of most loan borrowers
  3. What is the income range of borrowers, what income has majority of borrowers
  4. What are the categories of loan available for borrowers and what category is the most selected
  5. What year did people collect loan the most?
  6. What state is most borrower from?
  7. What prosper loan rating has the highest count
  8. What is the interest rate of most loans
  9. What is the employment status of most borrowers
  10. How many loan borrower is a home owner
  11. What is the debt to income ratio of most loan borrower
  12. What is the highest rating of loans

We can assume that alot of loan borrowers probably did not have a good paying job which may be the reason for taking loan.

After applying the log scale we ca see clearly now that most loan original amount is \$4,000 followed by \\$15,000 and \$10,000.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

LenderYield column has a normal distribution and there was no need for transformations

The only distribution with unusual point out of the variables I selected was Loan Original Amount which had its distribution right skewed, and log scale was used to properly visualise and interpret the distribution.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Loan Original Amount which had its distribution right skewed, and log scale was used to properly visualise and interpret the distribution.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

There a strong positive relationship between the following variables:

  • BorrowerRate and BorrowerAPR
  • BorrowerRate and LenderYield
  • LenderYield and BorrowerAPR
  • LenderYield and BorrowerRate
  • MonthlyloanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount

The positive correlation between MonthlyloanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount is logical because LoanOriginalAmount monthly is greatly dependent on the monthly income of a borrower

On the other hand heat map plot states that BorrowAPR and LoanOriginalAmount are negatively correlated

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  • There is a high interest rate on the loan status for past due payments which is normal because the longer it takes to pay loan the more the interest rate. It was observed that self-employed individuals have a higher percentage of defaulted loans than those who are unemployed which can be expected because their income might not be stable since they are not salary earners.
  • The income brackets between 25,000 and 49,999 take the majority of their loans for 36 months, followed by the group between 50,000 and 74,999. Loans are only taken out for 36 months by those with 0 income range.

We can observe that the BorrowAPR rises as the loan term lengthens for AA-B ratings, while for C-HR ratings, the BorrowAPR declines as the loan term lengthens.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • The loan amount increases as the credit rating improves, while the borrower APR decreases.
  • It was observed that employed people vary in terms of Loan Status and BorrowerAPR, as they have high borrower rates in chargeoffs and low borrower rates in past dues.
  • The APR for AA-B ratings rises as the loan term lengthens. For C to HR ratings, the APR decreases as the loan term lengthens.
  • A stronger credit score results in higher loan amounts and lower borrower APRs.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

  • BorrowerAPR and LoanOriginalAmount had a inverse relationship. The APR is typically lower for larger loan amounts.
  • Scatter plots and heatmaps were also created to discover that ProsperScore and BorrowerAPR were negatively correlated, as the higher the prosper score, the lower the risk attached, and thus the lower the APR, which further lowers the yield.
